Data Summary of Airbnb Listings in Sydney

Project 1

490357040, 490481703, 490411445, 490417311

University of Sydney | DATA1901 | Monday 12:00pm Lab 705-706 | August 2019


1 Executive Summary

The primary aim of this report is to uncover, if present, any associations between Sydney Airbnb accommodation prices and their corresponding geographic location. A secondary aim it to ask the same question for room type and the minimum nights a customer must stay.

The main discoveries include:

  • Prices per night are higher within a 10km range of the CBD and Northern Beaches;

  • Prices per night are lower when the distance is greater than 40km from the CBD;

  • Entire home listings generally require a higher minimum nights of stay; and

  • Shared room and private room listings share similar trends in minimum night requirements.


2 Full Report

2.1 Initial Data Analysis

2.1.1 Data Source

The dataset used to produce this report has been sourced from the website Inside Airbnb. Inside Airbnb scrapes publicly available information from Airbnb to provide monthly point in time datasets for a range of cities around the world. This report uses the July 2019 dataset for Sydney, which is treated as a sample for Sydneys Airbnb listings in general.

2.1.2 Data Reliability and Limitations

Readers should be aware that the datasets provided by Inside Airbnb do not constitute the primary datasets held by Airbnb. The process of web scraping may introduce errors in coding or interpretation, or deliberate tampering of observations. Further analyses may benefit from seeking primary data from Airbnb itself. Nonetheless, as a readily available dataset it is still a useful resource for conducting exploratory analyses.

2.1.3 Variable Classification

An initial data analysis shows the dataset comprises 15 variables describing 38,080 observations. Each row represents a single listing on Airbnb. As an individual listing can be a single room, there may be multiple listings for a single property. These cases cannot be identified as Airbnb applies random noise to latitude and longitude variables. Many continuous variables of interest are strongly right-skewed. This is dealt with on a case-by-case basis throughout the report. All variables of interest were correctly classified.

2.1.4 Stakeholders

Potential stakeholders include:

  • Property owners considering listing on Airbnb who are unsure of the price and minimum nights to set given their location and room type.
  • Local or State Governments who are interested in comparing listing prices and rental markets at given locations.
  • Current hosts who are interested in the competitiveness of their listing against similar listings. Hotel chains may be interested for similar reasons.

2.2 Research Question 1

Is there an association between the price of an Airbnb listing in Sydney and its geographical location with respect to the central business district (CBD)?

The global online accommodation platform, Airbnb, has experienced an exponential growth in listings and prices throughout Sydneys metropolitan and suburban areas. Costs of accommodation have been rising dramatically in parallel with increasing tourism figures, which counted 32.5 million visits in 2013-14 (Gurran & Phibbs 2017). Consequently, tourists have been branching out from traditional beachside and CBD destinations into more residential areas (Figure 1). Despite this migration, our analyses show that prices still peak in popular metropolitan and coastal suburbs.

###  code for map plot - Origin at Sydney CBD

airbnb <- read.csv("http://data.insideairbnb.com/australia/nsw/sydney/2019-07-10/visualisations/listings.csv")

uppermult <- 50 #multliplier for upper limit of price (multiple of IQR)
lowermult <- 5 #multliplier for lower limit of price (multiple of IQR)

airbnb_filt <- airbnb[airbnb$price < IQR(airbnb$price)*uppermult & airbnb$price > IQR(airbnb$price)*lowermult, ] 
#change the room type as well ("Private room, Entire home/apt, Shared room)  & (airbnb$room_type == "Entire home/apt")

Figure 1. Map of Airbnb price hotspots across Sydney

An initial investigation (Figure 2) shows that the price variable, representing the price per night for a listing, is heavily right-skewed (Md = $130, \(\bar{x}\) = $206, s = $389). The hot spots are found within 10km of the CBD and the Northern Beaches (30km north of the CBD), while prices steadily decline into suburban areas (40km west of the CBD).

g

Figure 2. Scatterplot of price per night in dollars against distance from listing to Sydney CBD in metres.

Listings located in Sydneys densely populated urban core (within a 5km range of the CBD) have the highest mean price per night of $190 (Md = $135, s = $444). The large standard deviation may be because the listings encompass a range of room types. This presents a limitation of the dataset. As the room_type variable is reduced to only three categories, we are prevented from properly controlling for any variability arising from significant differences within the type of listing. For example an entire house listing may be a one bedroom apartment, or a six bedroom house. Nonetheless, it is likely that proportionally more inner city listings are in high-density apartment blocks, which is important as 66% of all listings are within 8km of the CBD.

These findings are not surprising. Tourists are drawn in by attractions such as the Opera House and Bondi Beach, while residents are attracted to employment/business opportunities and public transport access. In short, as proximity to recreational areas and key attractions increases, intuitively, so too does the value and consequent asking price of a listing. Similarly, the Northern Beaches is imaged as an exclusive, desirable location, with highly accessible recreational areas and beaches. As a result these listings experience high demand, and can ask for high per night prices (Md = $450, \(\bar{x}\) = $654, s = $667). In opposition, suburban listings request significantly lower prices (Md = $120, \(\bar{x}\) = $190, s = $353). This may be due to various factors, such as a less dense residential population, or limited access to facilities, tourist attractions and international airports (Burnley & Murphy, 2013).

In summary we find that there is an association between the price of a listing and its geographical location. However this association is not limited to the CBD, but encompasses coastal hotspots also.

2.3 Research Question 2

Is there any association between the minimum number of nights required for a booking and the type of room available for an Airbnb listing in Sydney?

Like price, the minimum_night variable is heavily right-skewed, including two listings that require a minimum stay of 1000 nights (Figure 3).

However only a minority (1.2% of total) require a minimum stay of 32 nights or more, and distribution across room types is approximately the same as for shorter stays (Table 1). As with price outliers, this may be the direct result of a host manipulating their listings over time to drive or deter bookings.

Focusing only on bookings 31 nights or less, Figure 4 shows that one and two night minimums are the most common, with other peaks at predictable common values such as one or two weeks. It also shows that shared rooms are not a common type of listing.

## create histogram of min nights for all observations with a min stay of 31 nights or less
minNights31 = ggplot(listingMinNights31, aes(minimum_nights))
minNights31 + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, aes(fill = room_type)) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = colPalette) +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_text(margin = margin(t = 0, r = 10, b = 0, l = 0))) +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(margin = margin(t = 10, r = 0, b = 20, l = 0))) +

  xlab(paste("Minimum number of nights")) + 
  ylab("Number of listings")

Figure 4. Count of listings by minimum number of nights required and room type. Only includes listings with a minimum stay of 31 nights or less.

From Figure 5 we see that while all room types are right-skewed, the distribution of minimum nights is not consistent.

minNights31Box = ggplot(listingMinNights31, aes(x = room_type, y = minimum_nights, fill = room_type))
minNights31Box + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  coord_flip() + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = colPalette) +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_text(margin = margin(t = 0, r = 10, b = 0, l = 0))) +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(margin = margin(t = 10, r = 0, b = 20, l = 0))) +
  labs(fill = "Room Type") +
  xlab(paste("")) + 
  ylab("Number of listings")

Figure 5. Box plot of minimum number if nights required, grouped by room type. Only includes listings with a minimum stay of 31 nights or less.

The interquartile range (IQR) is narrowest for private rooms (Md = 2 nights), and even though there are outliers across all three room types, its upper quartile is also noticeably lower. Shared rooms also have a median of two nights, however in opposition it has the largest spread (IQR = 4 nights). This seems reasonable as people seek shared rooms for a range of reasons other than holiday-making, and the host may adjust their listing parametres to reflect the type of visitor they desire.

The entire home/apt room type has a higher median (= 3 nights) than other room types. Intuitively this may reflect practicalities on the hosts side, where a whole home or apartment takes more to clean, or requires the host to leave entirely. As a result they may only opt for multiple day bookings to make this worthwhile.

In summary, there is an association between the minimum number of nights and room type, with entire homes/apartments demanding slightly longer stays than private or shared rooms.
